SIMPLE: dissolvent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: dissolvent
<hw>dis*solv"ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>dissolvens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>dissolvere</ets>.]</ety> <def>Having power to dissolve power to
dissolve a solid body; <as>as, the <ex>dissolvent</ex> juices of the
stomach</as>.</def> <rj><au>Ray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dissolvent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dissolvent
<hw>Dis*solv"ent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which has the
power of dissolving or melting other substances, esp. by mixture with
them; a menstruum; a solvent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Melted in the crucible <qex>dissolvents</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>A.
Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The secret treaty of December acted as an immediate
<qex>dissolvent</qex> to the truce.</q> <rj><qau>Mothley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A remedy supposed capable of
dissolving concretions in the body, such as calculi, tubercles,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dissolver</ent>⟦br⟧
